{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"4a877e0a-3692-42b3-8961-3f34e126470e","content":"## `UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy = 1`\n\nThis setting (typically in `<startup useLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy=\"true\">` in app.config) changes how the CLR loads **legacy .NET 2.0/3.5 components**:\n\n**Without it (default):** COM components and mixed-mode (C++/CLI) assemblies built against CLR v2.0 trigger activation of the **v2.0 runtime**, requiring it to be installed side-by-side.\n\n**With it enabled (`1`):** Those same legacy components are loaded into the **CLR v4.x runtime** instead, using its backward-compatibility mode. The v2.0 runtime is never activated.\n\n**Key effects on runtime selection:**\n- **In-proc SxS is bypassed** for legacy components — they bind to v4.x.\n- Mixed-mode C++/CLI DLLs and legacy COM interop \"just work\" under v4.x without needing .NET 2.0/3.5 installed.\n- It only applies to **in-process** activation (COM, `ICLRRuntimeHost`); managed EXEs still select their runtime via their own config.\n\n**When you'd use it:** Hosting legacy v2.0 COM add-ins or mixed-mode plugins in a v4.x process (e.g., Office add-ins, MMC snap-ins).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"3da8e0ac-a49b-4c83-a16a-90172bd01dd8","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a specific CLR (Common Language Runtime) activation log message: \"UseLlegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy is set to 1\". This is a .NET Framework question about runtime activation behavior.\n\nLet me answer this from my knowledge about .NET CLR activation.\n\n`UseLegacyV2RuntimeActivationPolicy` is a configuration setting in .NET that affects how the CLR runtime is selected and activated, particularly for COM components and mixed-mode assemblies.\n\nWhen set to `1` (or `true`), it means:\n\n1. **What it does**: It binds legacy .NET 2.0 runtime activation policy to the chosen runtime (typically .NET 4.x). This means that COM components or mixed-mode C++/CLI assemblies that were built against .NET 2.0/3.5 will be loaded into the .NET 4.x runtime instead of requiring .NET 2.0 to be installed.\n\n\n2. **How it affects runtime selection**: Without this setting, the system would try to activate CLR v2.0 when loading legacy COM components or mixed-mode assemblies built for that version. With it enabled, CLR v4.0 handles these components using backward compatibility mode, typically configured in the app.config file's startup element.\n3. **In the activation log context**: The log message indicates that the hosting application has this policy enabled, allowing it to load older .NET 2.0/3.5 components into the newer runtime.","outputTokens":749,"requestId":"2C53:3E2EA0:13D89DD:1683D97:69F94A27"},"id":"72e10807-ae9f-496a-a70b-3acf54414344","timestamp":"2026-05-05T01:39:04.348Z","parentId":"57226036-2670-4fdb-a36a-3e453d99e565"}
